postal system works in a pretty similar way to this present day.

00:09:36.606 --> 00:09:39.056
Yet there was still a problem.

00:09:40.136 --> 00:09:48.056
What happened if you, as an Englishman in London let’s say, in 1870, wanted to send a letter

00:09:48.386 --> 00:09:54.826
to someone in another country, let’s say you wanted to send it to Rome, in Italy for example?

00:09:55.806 --> 00:09:58.606
Well, this was still very complicated.

00:09:59.456 --> 00:10:04.106
The letter that you wanted to send would, of course, have to travel

00:10:04.116 --> 00:10:08.096
through multiple different countries to get to its final destination.

00:10:09.126 --> 00:10:14.266
And if you were just buying a stamp when you sent the letter, in England,

00:10:14.576 --> 00:10:18.826
the English postal service wouldn’t take that letter all the way to Rome.

00:10:20.096 --> 00:10:24.766
