00:10:24.766 --> 00:10:30.416
mixture of different countries - perhaps France, Belgium, Germany,

00:10:30.426 --> 00:10:35.601
Switzerland, Austria, and others, before it even got anywhere near Rome.

00:10:37.211 --> 00:10:44.461
Any agreements that countries had in terms of managing their international post were normally

00:10:44.471 --> 00:10:51.051
bilateral, they were between two countries, so you would have to send your post first to

00:10:51.051 --> 00:10:56.881
someone in France, then they would have to forward it on to someone in Switzerland, and

00:10:56.911 --> 00:11:04.001
they would have to send it on to someone in Italy, to your eventual destination in Rome.

00:11:04.101 --> 00:11:07.671
There was no system in place for post to go from one

00:11:07.671 --> 00:11:11.451
country to another but to pass through another on the way.

00:11:12.911 --> 00:11:17.271
Obviously, that was a massive hassle, and very expensive.

00:11:18.561 --> 00:11:24.411
Yet now, I can send a letter from a small island in Europe to a small island in

00:11:24.411 --> 00:11:29.841
the Pacific for less than the cost of a cup of coffee, and it is incredibly easy.

00:11:30.751 --> 00:11:31.601
What changed?

00:11:33.131 --> 00:11:38.541
Well, it was clear to everyone that this original system wasn’t going to work.

00:11:39.481 --> 00:11:41.631
But how could it be simplified?

00:11:42.911 --> 00:11:50.391
In 1874, a congress was called, led by a man called Ernst Heinrich Wilhelm von Stephan.

00:11:51.831 --> 00:11:58.011
Von Stephan is the man credited with simplifying the German postal system, and he

00:11:58.021 --> 00:12:04.531
implemented and improved on a lot of the ideas that Hill had suggested in England.

00:12:06.111 --> 00:12:10.571
Von Stephan had a grand plan for how international postage should

00:12:10.571 --> 00:12:16.281
work, and he presented this plan to representatives from 22 countries.

00:12:17.931 --> 00:12:19.141
The plan was simple.

00:12:19.971 --> 00:12:27.821
Firstly, that there should be a uniform, flat rate to send a letter anywhere in the world.

00:12:29.321 --> 00:12:36.581
Secondly, the postal authorities should give equal treatment to foreign and domestic mail.

00:12:37.011 --> 00:12:39.501
They couldn’t prioritise the domestic post.

00:12:40.231 --> 00:12:42.721
Every letter should be treated the same.

00:12:44.301 --> 00:12:50.891
And thirdly, that each country should keep all money it has collected for international postage.

00:12:51.411 --> 00:12:57.738
So in my earlier example of sending a letter from England to Rome, the

00:12:57.748 --> 00:13:01.608
British postal service gets all of the money from the cost of the stamp.

00:13:02.148 --> 00:13:06.488
The French, German, Swiss, Italian, or whatever other

00:13:06.748 --> 00:13:09.988
postal services helped deliver the letter get nothing.

00:13:11.568 --> 00:13:14.608
Now, you might think, well that’s a bit unfair.

00:13:14.988 --> 00:13:20.638
Surely the British postal service should share some of that money, as they only did

00:13:20.638 --> 00:13:26.218
the easy part of collecting the letter and perhaps putting it on a ship to France.

00:13:26.228 --> 00:13:31.178
The reason that Von Stephan proposed this system, where

00:13:31.178 --> 00:13:34.828
the sending country got all the money was quite simple.

00:13:35.758 --> 00:13:41.098
Firstly, it was simpler to not have to add up all of the costs and

00:13:41.098 --> 00:13:44.698
share them with each country that had been involved in the delivery.

00:13:46.278 --> 00:13:51.258
This would require a lot of administration, and therefore cost.

00:13:52.848 --> 00:14:00.458
But secondly, the idea was that each letter that was sent would receive a response, so in this

00:14:00.488 --> 00:14:07.165
example, your friend in Rome would write a letter back, in this case the Italian postal service

00:14:07.305 --> 00:14:12.315
would collect the money from the cost of the stamp, and the British one would get nothing.

00:14:12.825 --> 00:14:15.505
So it would all even itself out.

00:14:17.185 --> 00:14:23.205
And before you say, hang on, what about the French, German or Swiss postal service,

00:14:23.725 --> 00:14:29.855
yes, in this example they aren’t getting anything, but the expensive part of the postal

00:14:29.855 --> 00:14:35.225
system isn’t the bit in the middle, it’s the bit at the start and the bit at the end.

00:14:36.775 --> 00:14:41.295
All of the countries at the congress accepted Von Stephan’s suggestions,

00:14:41.975 --> 00:14:47.445
and in 1874 something called the General Postal Union was formed.

00:14:48.525 --> 00:14:55.325
It quickly attracted countries from all over the world, and just 5 years later it changed its

00:14:55.325 --> 00:15:02.335
name to the Universal Postal Union, to reflect the fact that, well, it was almost universal.

00:15:03.895 --> 00:15:08.505
This system of only the sending country getting the money for postage

00:15:08.795 --> 00:15:13.365
was to prove a little problematic though, and certainly unfair.

00:15:14.975 --> 00:15:18.405
It benefited countries that sent more mail than they

00:15:18.405 --> 00:15:23.195
received, and for some countries, there was a large imbalance.

00:15:24.755 --> 00:15:30.165
In 1906 it was found that the Italian postal service was delivering

00:15:30.165 --> 00:15:38.645
325,000 magazines every year to addresses in Italy, yet a grand total

00:15:38.785 --> 00:15:43.955
of zero magazines were sent by the Italian postal service abroad.

00:15:45.555 --> 00:15:50.975
As a member of the Universal Postal Union, Italy had to deliver these in

00:15:50.975 --> 00:15:56.235
effect for free, and understandably, complained that the system wasn’t fair.

00:15:57.915 --> 00:16:06.512
However, for 53 years, the Universal Postal Union, the UPU, remained broadly unchanged.

00:16:08.208 --> 00:16:13.685
But as the process of decolonisation started to happen after the end

00:16:13.705 --> 00:16:20.165
of the Second World War, and these new countries joined the UPU they,

00:16:20.325 --> 00:16:25.245
like Italy, ended up receiving a lot more mail than they sent out.

00:16:26.485 --> 00:16:32.595
Richer countries, such as France, Britain, and US, were making money by

00:16:32.605 --> 00:16:37.307
sending much more letters than they received, and the poorer countries,

00:16:37.327 --> 00:16:42.087
these ex-colonies, were delivering the mail and not getting paid for it.

00:16:43.647 --> 00:16:47.597
They pushed for change, and there was enough pressure within

00:16:47.597 --> 00:16:53.417
the UPU to create a new system, called “terminal dues”.

00:16:54.827 --> 00:17:00.887
What this meant was that if there was an imbalance, a difference, between the weight

00:17:00.937 --> 00:17:07.107
of the post sent and received between two countries, then one country had to pay

00:17:07.107 --> 00:17:13.857
the other an amount of money set by the UPU, based on how large the difference was.

00:17:15.537 --> 00:17:18.967
It sounds like an improvement, and it definitely was to

00:17:18.967 --> 00:17:22.637
a certain extent, but there was another issue with this.

00:17:24.057 --> 00:17:29.977
The amount of money was the same for every country in the world, so the countries

00:17:29.997 --> 00:17:35.059
with low-cost postal services, either because they had low-cost labour, or

00:17:35.079 --> 00:17:40.259
because they were very efficient, they benefited from this, as they got more

00:17:40.269 --> 00:17:45.329
money in compensation than it actually cost them to deliver the letters.

00:17:46.216 --> 00:17:53.313
If you receive a million dollars as compensation for delivering lots of post, but actually it only

00:17:53.313 --> 00:17:59.924
costs you $500,000 to deliver that post, well done, that's some profit for your postal service.

00:18:01.614 --> 00:18:07.536
This situation has, to a certain extent, now been improved countries

00:18:07.546 --> 00:18:11.956
are put into one of four different categories depending on how developed

00:18:11.956 --> 00:18:16.646
they are, and the categories pay different levels of terminal dues.

00:18:18.029 --> 00:18:25.693
But the situation is still far from perfect, and there seems to be a perennial battle over

00:18:25.693 --> 00:18:32.263
what is the right amount of compensation for a country that delivers more mail than it sends.

00:18:34.003 --> 00:18:37.553
You may have heard Donald Trump complaining about the postal

00:18:37.553 --> 00:18:42.193
service, and this is partly because of the terminal dues system.

00:18:43.803 --> 00:18:47.663
The United States threatened to withdraw from the UPU.

00:18:47.663 --> 00:18:54.633
the Universal Postal Union, in 2018, as it claimed it was subsidising

00:18:54.813 --> 00:18:59.533
the cost of packages that arrived from abroad, particularly from China.

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:07.257
The Americans demanded a system of self-declaration, where it decided how

00:19:07.257 --> 00:19:13.837
much to charge foreign postal services to deliver their post, not the UPU.

00:19:15.337 --> 00:19:21.327
An American exit from the UPU would have been very disruptive to the global economy.

00:19:22.247 --> 00:19:29.057
The country handles about half of the world’s mail, and the UPU didn’t have much of a choice.

00:19:30.647 --> 00:19:38.867
So, pressed against the wall, it agreed to the US requests, and from July 2020 the US

00:19:38.897 --> 00:19:44.217
will be allowed to set its own rates that it charges foreign postal services, but these

00:19:44.217 --> 00:19:50.707
rates can be a maximum of 70 percent of the domestic cost, the cost within that country.

00:19:52.207 --> 00:19:58.657
Naturally, this cost is going to be passed on to consumers, and some have said that the

00:19:58.707 --> 00:20:04.677
era of ultra-low cost shipping from places like China to America is going to be over.

00:20:05.537 --> 00:20:12.127
And if, instead of buying an iPhone case from China for $5 with free shipping, it’s going to

00:20:12.127 --> 00:20:19.307
be $5 and $5 for the shipping, suddenly that iPhone case becomes slightly less attractive.

00:20:20.290 --> 00:20:24.132
It’s surely a good thing for the United States manufacturing

00:20:24.132 --> 00:20:27.632
industry, as suddenly it becomes a lot more competitive.

00:20:29.222 --> 00:20:34.062
But whether it is a good thing for the consumer is another question altogether.

00:20:35.662 --> 00:20:40.872
Certainly Sir Rowland Hill, the inventor of the modern postal service as we know

00:20:40.872 --> 00:20:45.932
it, wouldn’t be particularly happy to see the direction the UPU is going in.

00:20:46.902 --> 00:20:52.142
A more complicated system that raises the cost of the postal system was

00:20:52.192 --> 00:20:57.852
everything he stood against, and I imagine that he would be turning in his grave.

